        <td>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box" style="font-style:italic;" translate="true">(Wikipedia Definition) </text><text styleclass="Popup Box2" translate="true">Kinematic-Chain</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" style="font-style:italic;" translate="true"> refers to an assembly of rigid bodies connected by joints that is the mathematical model for a mechanical system. As in the familiar use of the word chain, the rigid bodies, or links, are constrained by their connections to other links. &#160;</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Normal"><line style="height:1px; color:#993300;" /></para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box" style="font-style:italic;" translate="true">(MechDesigner Definition): A </text><text styleclass="Popup Box2" translate="true">Kinematic-Chains</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true"> is a minimum of two </text><text styleclass="Element" translate="true">Parts</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">, that are joined with </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="MD-Joint" styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">Joints</link><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">, with a minimum of one Joint. </text></para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">We list the kinematic-chains in the </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="MD-Kinematics-Tree" styleclass="Popup Box2" translate="true">Kinematics-Tree</link><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">. </text></para>
